{{about|the Ministry of the Justice <u>after 1871</u>||Ministry of Justice (Ritsuryō)}}
{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = Ministry of Justice |nativename = 法務省 |nativename_a = Hōmu-shō |nativename_r = |logo = |logo_width = |logo_caption = |seal = |seal_width = |seal_caption = |picture = Ministry of Justice Japan04s3200.jpg |picture_width = |picture_caption = The Ministry of Justice building |formed = {{start_date|1948|02|15}} |preceding1 = {{nihongo|Ministry of Justice|司法省|Shihōshō}} ({{start_date|1871|07|09}} - {{end_date|1948|02|15}}) |preceding2 = |dissolved = |superseding = |jurisdiction = {{JPN}} |headquarters = 1-1-1 [[Kasumigaseki]], [[Chiyoda, Tokyo|Chiyoda-ku]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]] |employees = |budget = |minister1_name = [[Takashi Yamashita]] |minister1_pfo = [[Minister of Justice (Japan)|Minister of Justice]] |minister2_name = [[Hiroshi Hiraguchi]] |minister2_pfo = State Minister of Justice |minister3_name = Hiroaki Kadoyama |minister3_pfo = Parliamentary Vice-Minister of Justice |parent_agency = [[Government of Japan]] |child1_agency = Immigration Bureau |child2_agency = |website = http://www.moj.go.jp |footnotes = }} [[File:Tokyo detention center.jpg|thumb|[[Tokyo Detention House]]]]
The {{Nihongo|'''Ministry of Justice'''|法務省|Hōmu-shō}} is one of the cabinet level ministries of the [[Japanese government]]. It is responsible for the judicial system, correctional services, household, property and corporate registrations, and also serves as the government legal representatives. The ministry also houses the Immigration Bureau.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.immi-moj.go.jp/english/|title=Immigration Bureau of Japan Website|last=Bureau|first=Immigration|website=www.immi-moj.go.jp|language=en|access-date=2017-02-12}}</ref>
==Meiji Constitution== The Ministry of Justice was established under the [[Meiji Constitution|Constitution of the Empire of Japan]] in 1871 as the {{nihongo|Ministry of Justice|司法省|Shihōshō}}.
==Constitution of Japan== The Ministry acquired its present name under the post-war [[Constitution of Japan]] in 1952. Its responsibilities include administration of [[Judicial system of Japan|Japan's judicial system]] and [[penal system of Japan|penal system]]. It represents the Japanese government in [[litigation]], and is also responsible for maintenance of government registration of families, resident [[Alien (law)|alien]]s, [[real estate]] and [[corporation]]s.
The Ministry has jurisdiction over the National Bar Examination Commission, the Public Security Examination Commission, and the [[Public Security Intelligence Agency]]. Although the [[Public Prosecutor]]'s Offices are administratively part of the Ministry of Justice, they are independent from the authority of the Minister of Justice.
At the top of the ministry is the [[Minister of Justice (Japan)|Minister of Justice]], a member of the [[Cabinet of Japan|Cabinet]], and he or she is chosen by the [[Prime Minister of Japan|Prime Minister]] typically from members of the [[National Diet]].
