The '''Society of Composers, Authors and Music Publishers of Canada''' ('''SOCAN''') is a Canadian [[performance rights organisation]] that represents the performing rights of more than 135,000 songwriters, composers and music publishers. The organization collects licence fees through a music licensing program approved by the [[Copyright Board of Canada]].<ref name="CE">{{cite book|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/socan/|title=SOCAN|work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]| first= Andrew | last= McIntosh|date=August 29, 2013}}</ref>
==History== SOCAN is a result of a merger that took place in 1990 between the Composers, Authors and Publishers Association of Canada (CAPAC) and the Performing Rights Organization of Canada (PROCAN).<ref name= CE />
In May 2016, SOCAN acquired the Seattle-based company Medianet Digital for an undisclosed amount; the organization planned to leverage the company's software and database of rights metadata to assist in the calculation and distribution of royalties for works on digital music streaming services.<ref name="gandm-medianet">{{cite web|title=SOCAN acquisition to help Canadian musicians collect royalties|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/technology/socan-acquisition-to-help-canadian-musicians-collect-royalties/article29989718/|website=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=19 August 2016}}</ref> In July 2016, SOCAN acquired Audiam, a U.S. startup created by [[TuneCore]] founder Jeff Price that specializes in managing the distribution of royalties for songs used on digital services such as [[YouTube]], using a database of song recordings and metadata for identification.<ref name="billboard-audiam">{{cite web|title=Canada's SOCAN Acquires Digital Rights Firm Audiam| url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7445889/socan-acquires-audiam|work= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=19 August 2016}}</ref><ref name= "wsj-audiam">{{cite web|title=Audiam Raises $2M to ‘Get People Paid’ for Use of their Music on YouTube |url= https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2014/03/04/audiam-raises-2m-to-get-people-paid-for-use-of-their-music-on-youtube/ |website= [[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=19 August 2016}}</ref>
